When you write a class, JavaScript builds the same prototype structures you could build by hand. But a few things — real private fields especially — genuinely cannot be reproduced with prototypes. Here’s where the ‘just sugar’ story breaks down.

4 min read
2 hours ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Photo by Jed Owen on Unsplash“Classes are just syntactic sugar over prototypes.” It is one of those lines people repeat to show they understand what is going on underneath. And it is mostly right — a class really does compile down to the constructor functions and prototype chains from earlier this season. But the word “just” is quietly hiding a few features that prototypes genuinely cannot reproduce. This article separates the sugar from the real additions.

🎙 This is the Season 2 finale of Oh, That’s Why. — hosted by Alex Vega. The podcast answers the “are classes real?” question honestly through a prefab-house-kit analogy, pulling together the whole season. Link in the footer.
Last week we finished the two-part series on this — call, apply, bind, and arrow functions. This week, the finale, everything from the season converges: the prototype chain, property descriptors, and this all combine to explain exactly what the class keyword does.

Think about building a house two ways. From raw lumber and hand tools, you cut every beam and wire up every join yourself — that is prototype-based JavaScript, writing constructor functions and attaching methods to prototypes by hand. It works, but it is error-prone. A prefab house kit arrives with the framing pre-cut and the joins engineered to fit — you assemble the same house, faster and with fewer mistakes. That is the class keyword. As Alex explains in the episode, classes are mostly the kit for the same prototype house. But a couple of fixtures in the kit — genuinely private fields — are sealed units you cannot build from raw lumber at all.
What is genuinely sugar
Methods go on the prototype. When you write a class with methods, JavaScript builds a constructor function and puts every method on its prototype — shared by all instances, exactly as if you had attached them by hand.
class User {
constructor(name) {
this.name = name;
}
greet() {
return `Hi, I’m ${this.name}`;
}
}// Roughly compiles to:
function User(name) {
this.name = name;
}
User.prototype.greet = function () {
return `Hi, I’m ${this.name}`;
};
Static members go on the class itself — attached to the constructor function, not the prototype, and called on the class rather than instances.
class MathHelper {
static square(n) {
return n * n;
}
}MathHelper.square(5); // 25 — called on the class, not an instance
extends and super wire up the chain. extends sets up two prototype links automatically — one so instance methods inherit, one so static methods inherit super calls the parent constructor or a parent method.
class Animal {
constructor(legs) { this.legs = legs; }
describe() { return `Has ${this.legs} legs`; }
}class Dog extends Animal {
constructor(name) {
super(4); // call parent constructor
this.name = name;
}
}
new Dog(“Max”).describe(); // “Has 4 legs” — inherited via the chain
What is NOT just sugar
Private fields with #. Enforced by the language itself, not by convention. Code outside the class cannot read, write, or even detect them — and this is not part of the prototype model. You cannot reproduce true private fields with prototypes.
Closures and WeakMaps approximate privacy, but the # syntax is real, language-level enforcement the prototype system does not reach.
class Account {
#balance = 0; // truly private — enforced by the language
deposit(amount) {
this.#balance += amount;
return this.#balance;
}
}const acc = new Account();
acc.deposit(100); // 100
acc.#balance; // SyntaxError — cannot be accessed from outside
A few more genuine differences: a class throws if called without new (a plain constructor function silently misbehaves instead), and class bodies run in strict mode automatically. Small, but real behavioral additions.
Class methods are regular functions and follow all four this binding rules. Pull a method off an instance and pass it as a callback, and it loses its this exactly as covered in the last two episodes — classes do not protect you. The fixes are the same: bind in the constructor, or use an arrow function class field that captures this lexically. Also: inside a static method, this is the class itself, not an instance —and private static fields should be accessed through the class name, not this, because through inheritance this may be a subclass that lacks the field.
class Timer {
constructor() {
this.seconds = 0;
// arrow field captures this lexically — safe as a callback
this.tick = () => { this.seconds++; };
}
}const t = new Timer();
setInterval(t.tick, 1000); // works — arrow field kept this
A class is a cleaner way to build the same prototype structures — constructor, methods, inheritance — with a few genuine additions like real private fields that go beyond sugar. Same house, mostly from a kit.
Did you think of classes as pure syntactic sugar before today? Does knowing that private fields are genuinely not reproducible with prototypes change how you weigh classes against factory functions?

That is the end of Season 2. Season 3 — how JavaScript handles time: the event loop, callbacks, promises, and async/await. Why some of your code runs now, some runs later, and why the order so often surprises you.
🎙 The podcast finale connects the whole season — prototype chain, descriptors, and this — into one explanation of the class keyword, through the prefab-kit analogy. If you have followed Season 2 from the start, that landing is worth hearing. Find Oh, That’s Why. wherever you listen to podcasts.

Thanks for reading Season 2. Two seasons in, you understand how JavaScript runs and how it handles data — most of the language, from the inside.
